</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="86" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="1" pageNumber="86">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="1" pageNumber="86">
After 
<bibRefCitation author="Viraktamath, CA" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="8" pageNumber="93" pagination="1 - 118" title="Revision of the Oriental and Australian Agalliini (Hemiptera: Cicadellidae: Megophthalminae)." volume="2844" year="2011">Viraktamath (2011)</bibRefCitation>
. This genus is similar to other two 
<taxonomicName lsidName="" pageId="1" pageNumber="86" rank="tribe" tribe="Agalliini">Agalliini</taxonomicName>
genera, 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Agallia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Agallia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="86" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Agallia</taxonomicName>
Curtis, 1833 and 
<taxonomicName authority="Viraktamath, 2011" authorityName="Viraktamath" authorityYear="2011" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Formallia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Formallia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="86" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Formallia</taxonomicName>
Viraktamath, 2011: it closely resembles 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Agallia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Agallia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="86" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Agallia</taxonomicName>
in having stout setae on the ventral margin of the male subgenital plate but differs in having hairlike setae on the male pygofer side and subgenital plate and in the shapes of the aedeagus and subgenital plates; it is also similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Viraktamath, 2011" authorityName="Viraktamath" authorityYear="2011" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Formallia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Formallia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="86" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Formallia</taxonomicName>
in body appearance but differs in having setae both dorsally and ventrally on the subgenital plates and also in the shapes of the male pygofer, connective, and aedeagus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
